1) Who developed Java, and in which year?
-->The Java programming language was developed by James Gosling and his team (known as the "Green Team") at Sun Microsystems in the early 1990s. 
It was first publicly released in 1995


2) What was Java originally called, and why was it renamed?
-->Java was originally named Oak (and briefly GreenTalk) in 1991, created by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems. It was renamed to Java in 1994–1995
    after finding that "Oak" was already trademarked by Oak Technologies, necessitating a change.

3) Why was Java developed?
-->Java was developed to create a platform-independent language for embedded devices and interactive television, as existing languages like C++ were
    too complex and platform-dependent for this purpose. The goal was a "write once, run anywhere" (WORA) capability.

4) Which company currently owns Java?
-->Oracle Corporation currently owns Java. Oracle acquired the rights to the Java platform,
    brand, and technologies when they purchased Sun Microsystems in January 2010. 

5) In which year was Java first released publicly?
-->Java was first released publicly in 1995. The initial public alpha and beta 
    versions were available in May 1995, as a core component of Sun Microsystems' Java platform.

6) What is the significance of the Java 1.0 release?
-->Released in January 1996, Java 1.0 (JDK 1.0) was significant as the first official release of the Java programming language by Sun Microsystems.

7) How has Java evolved from JDK 1.0 to the latest version?
-->Java has evolved from a basic, platform-independent language in JDK 1.0 to a robust, high-performance platform 
    supporting modern paradigms like functional programming and lightweight concurrency. 

8) What is the difference between Java SE, EE, and ME in terms of release history?
-->The primary difference in release history for Java SE, EE, and ME is that Java SE is the foundational platform with a consistent,
    independent versioning and release cycle, while Java EE and Java ME are extensions built on top of Java SE and have release cycles 
    that have historically been tied to, but often lag behind, the relevant Java SE version
