9) Why is Java called a platform-independent language?
-->Java is called a platform-independent language because of its "Write Once, Run Anywhere" (WORA) capability,
    which allows compiled Java code (bytecode) to run on any operating system (Windows, Linux, macOS) without modification. 
    This is achieved by compiling source code into intermediate bytecode rather than platform-specific native code. 
    Key elements enabling this feature include:
    Bytecode: The Java compiler translates code into a universal intermediate form (a .class file) instead of machine-specific code.
    Java Virtual Machine (JVM): The JVM is installed on different operating systems to interpret this bytecode, translating it into machine
    instructions specific to the current platform


10) What made Java more popular than other languages during its early release?
-->Java gained rapid popularity upon its 1995 release due to its revolutionary "Write Once, Run Anywhere" (WORA) capability.

